segments.text: When did you first meet Dr. Francis?
When he taught me a course in Veterinary Anatomy when I was a junior in animal husbandry.
That was in the year 21-22.
He was a little different than the usual one.
He would have been a pretty good one for the stage, I think.
He did everything in pantomime.
And he could imitate a horse with a string halt to perfection.
He'd drag that leg across the room.
Or a lame horse.
And he'd show how they acted, but he was just a comic as far as a lecture.
Later, a number of years later, I heard a story that Dr. Bowden, who was dean from 48 to 53,
When he was a senior student at Ohio State University, that's where Dr. Francis graduated.
Dr. Francis graduated there in 87.
When he was a senior student, he was a class of 16, and when he was a senior student, the dean at Ohio State invited Dr. Francis to lecture to the veterinary students.
And he went up there for a week to lecture.
And each succeeding day, well, they'd have business.
And they'd get to growing and growing and growing.
They wanted to see that little man, cute little man lecture.
But he was a good lecturer, but did so much in pantomime.
He was a good mimic.
But the dean of engineering heard him.
and talked him into staying over a whole week, mind you, and lectured to the engineering students.
And they did the same thing, yes.
What would he lecture to them about?
Well, just, I don't know, but it was probably stories of one kind or another.
He was interested in paleontology.
He had a wide
knowledge, but old citizenship and a little of everything.
After he lost his hearing, he had influenza or something.
I left him with very hard of hearing, and that was pretty...
I don't know what year that happened.
It was before my time.
But he would buy a hearing device every time somebody had a new hearing device.
He'd buy it, give it away.
He wouldn't return it.
He'd just give it away to somebody else.
He said it was convenient not to hear.
But was a wonderful lip reader.
I've been in his office, and his secretary and I would be talking.
Dr. Francis would come down and sit across here, and he'd look from one to the other.
And we could know that he was lip reading, so every time I'd answer her, I'd turn to him.
And he'd join in conversation.
And he couldn't hear a word we were saying, but he went right through it.
He did things his own way.

For example, at commencement, every dean would get up and announce formally, of course, by the power invested in me and so forth and so forth, I present to you, the president, to the following students and either
civil engineering or mechanical engineering or economics or whatnot, agriculture.
And I remember Alan Ward finished, I think, the only man in 28.
And we had commencement in Guyon Hall.
And oh, it was hot by that time in May, latter part of May.
No air conditioning.
And when his time, Dean Kyle, of course, would get up in agriculture in his slow voice and take that year to go through every word of that formality.
By the time veterinary medicine, that was the last one.
And he said, Ward, stand up.
Come get it.
That was all.
He didn't say by the power invested in me and all that, he said.
And Ward would make that long walk down there, and of course by that time everybody would applaud him, but everybody would laugh.
They were awake by that time.
They always stayed to hear Dr. Francis.
And when Ty Hardy, later he's retired from the Experiment Station at Sonora, same thing, says, Hardy, stand up, come and get it.
and that was his way of ending the commencement.
But he got by with things like that.
It was probably the best thing in the world he could have done, but gave them a humorous view part of it.
What kind of relations did he as a teacher have with his students?
Oh, excellent.
He was a very compassionate man.
He knew the quality of the students.
He didn't need to give final examinations.
How he evaluated students' performances, I do not know.
I never learned that.
I studied him and studied him.
I helped him out with some of his classes.
I never knew how he could evaluate a student.
But when he came to the final grades, they were right down the line.
He didn't give them an exam?
He just gave a grade?
Oh, yes.
He'd give us How would he quiz you on that?
Not orally, of course, because he couldn't hear, but he'd give us occasionally
bring a pad of Form B in there.
He said, OK, we're going to have an exam today.
In general discussion, describe all the structures in here or there.
And you had to know something about it.
You mean snap quizzes he'd give you?
Or would he tell you in advance?
Oh, he would tell us.
No, I don't think he ever gave us a pop quiz.
He may have, but I don't recall.
But in the class of 36, there were two students who had grades that mid-semester had grades reversed, I think.
How, I don't know.
It was probably an error, either in the registrar's office or either the secretary may have transposed them.
But one was Charles Steger from Dallas, who was an A student in everything.
And we had some excellent students in that class.
I think there was 16 students in that class and about, I'd say 12 or 14 were straight A students.
Oh, they were good students.
And so one of the
Boris came to me.
He was later an instructor in medicine surgery.
He was a boy from California.
He said, would you ask Dr. Francis if he hasn't made an error in Charles Stegers?
He was a buddy of Charles.
They worked in the lab together.
And with so-and-so and called this other boy's name from Puerto Rico.
I said, oh, no.
I said, I'm not going to bother him about grades.
I said, those are not a part of your final grades.
I said, the error will be, if it's an error, it'll be corrected.
As a matter of curiosity, the following week, I just wrote him a note.
I said, what kind of work is Charles Digger?
He said, oh, he's a top student.
I said, that boy's an A student, isn't he?
And they had a C posted for him.
And I said, what do you think about this man?
I was thinking about this Puerto Rican.
He said, oh, he comes in late every time.
He's the first one to leave.
And while he's there, he doesn't do a damn thing.
He had them already.
He knew them.
And he had an A posted.
Probably the only A he ever had while he was in school.
by the end of the semester, why he had the grades, as I should have been.
But I wasn't going to bother him.
It wasn't my part to straighten things out.
But that was one little thing, things like that that I enjoyed being with him.
He had a knack of teaching.
Do you think he enjoyed teaching?
Oh, yes, very much so.
And he had a sharp wit.
In fact, I remember two men who, oh, in the last few years said, do you ever watch, that was when Arthur Fiedler was at his top, that was about six or eight years ago,
If I ever watched the Boston Pops Orchestra, I said, yes.
He says, who does Arthur Fiedler remind you of?
I said, Dr. Francis.
He said, yes, that's exactly.
His hair, his white hair, the way he walked, sharp steps.
Of course, Fiedler in his last year, he was shuffling a little bit more.
And his mannerisms.
or right down the line in his general appearance.
He looked very much that mustache, appearance very similar to Dr. Francis.
But, well, he was a great man.
I remember, pardon me.
He was,
had a great interest in paleontology.
In fact, he had a pretty good museum down here at one time.
And collected bones, people would send specimens in for him or tell him about the gravel pit up around Waco or down around close to Sealy or down close to Houston.
And he'd go and dig them up.
And he had some big dinosaur bones and stuff like that, and teeth.
And we'd go down after every, when the Brazos River would get out of bounds or have a flood, after every flood, we'd go down.
And I went with him on a number of trips.
He'd always go in his collection.
and put about, oh, a half a dozen, depending on how many would go with us.
I'd use my car, and we'd carry several, and he'd put these in his pocket.
When he'd get down there, he'd walk ahead.
We'd be busy with something.
He'd give us something to look at.
He'd go down and scatter these horse teeth.
from his collection of prehistoric horse.
So he come back and everybody found something.
Well, you do pull mischief like that.
So I went one weekend from Friday until Sunday.
We spent in Houston.
Somebody had written him a letter about a specimen down in the bio somewhere that they had found.
But he wanted to go down there and look at it.
And I took him down there in my car, and we stayed at the old McAtee Hotel right across from the Grand Central Station Railroad, both gone now.
But after we checked in, we went up to an 8th Friday evening.
We ate at the Sanger Center Hotel there on Main Street, the corner of Main and I don't know whether that's Dallas or Walker.
It's right across.
The Sanger Center now is the Marr Hotel.
The Marr extends from
from Maine to, or the street to west of that, I've forgotten what the name of it is.
But right across the street from Foley's, right north of Foley's, that's the Lamar Hotel.
Well, right on the corner of Maine, standing back about half the block, was the San Jacinto Hotel, and that was a favorite meeting place for people who'd go down and shop from around this community.
And so we ate supper there, and so
He didn't hear what I was ordering.
He was a ham and egger.
And he came.
He had ham and eggs.
And I had a stuffed crab.
And he looked over there at mine.
And he says, Burns?
He said, I want to get home.
And he says, I hope you don't get sick on that.
He said, we're planning to stay till Sunday.
You know, people leave home, they start eating things that they're not accustomed to eating.
And he says, it's wrong.
They ought to eat pretty much safe things that they eat at home.
And he says, there you are eating, of all things, a shellfish, a stuffed crab.
And he says, this is Friday night.
He says, you know what they've been doing here at the Santa Center since Monday morning?
They've been saving table scraps to stuff that crab you're eating.
Well, for breakfast, of course, I ordered bacon and eggs, ham and eggs.
And then for lunch, I ate ham and eggs the rest of the time.
And he says, you know, you're getting smart.
But we went to...
The old Metropolitan Theater, it was brand new then, and it was one of the first theaters that had that organ, you know, that was hydraulic.
And so the picture show was, back in those days, B.B.
Daniels was the reigning, probably the female actress at that time, the top one.

But she was in a polo, playing polo, and it was in South America, I've forgotten the picture, and she was riding this polo pony, and her left leg slipped through the stove, and then she was hanging on to the horn, to the saddle.
And Dr. Francis got up out of there, see, and he, and everybody around there got to yelling at him, laughing at him, see, a peculiar little fellow.
And he rode every step until she was safe.
Somebody stopped that horse.
Well, right in the middle of the picture show, we were sitting downstairs, about a third from the front and the center.
Very prominent.
Every way you could see were people up in the balconies and back hours.
And the lights went out.
And...
Immediately, Dr. Francis reached in his coat pocket and struck a match and lit this candle.
And that was after this trick of this photo match.
And the people got to laughing at him.
He says, Burns, people panic in the complete darkness.
And it was completely dark.
He says, people panic.
And he said, all they need to see is a little ray of light.
And all of us were laughing at him.
It was a show.
And then we got home.
He says, you know, I'll tell you something about that candle.
He said, I was out in West Texas.
He used to travel.
When he came here in 88,
Of course, he had very little teaching, taught agriculture to students, but he did a lot of research and did a lot of extension work and traveled all over the state.
And he was out in West Texas, and he said, that was the day before they'd have a toilet in each room.
And he says, the toilet would be down by one on each floor.
And he said, way down at the end of the hall.
And he says, during the night I got up as usual and said, I walked down there and said, I thought I counted rooms going down there so I could get my way back.
They were dark.
And he says, I counted rooms and I stopped a little bit too soon and I opened the door and a woman screamed.
And he says, ever since then I've carried a candle with me.
He says, I'll never leave home without a candle.
He had a lot of fun about him.
Do you think he liked being the dean?
Well, from the time I knew him, he really didn't.
Dr. Marsteller took care of the dean's duties as far as registration and stuff like that.
He was in demand as a lecturer, but he had stopped that by the time I got started taking veterinary medicine.
That was back in the 16 when he went up there to lecture.
I guess he got tired of it or something.
He couldn't hear.
But he had stopped it.
But he would like to go to .
He never did drive a car.
Why not?
They were on the Buick.
Mrs. Francis drove them all, any place he wanted to go.
But he would never miss a Shirley Temple show.
Really?
Yeah, he'd go to picture shows with her.
But another thing I remember about him, he picked up the newspaper one day, and I think he was taking Dallas News, and he said, look there.
on the sports page.
He says, the Yanks slaughtered the Indians.
He said, now what would a foreign student over here from the East, and we still had foreign students, not as many as we have now.
But you did have some, huh?
Oh, yes.
And he says, what would a foreign student think about?
Mainly South America or Mexico.
What would a foreign student
How could he read those lines on the page?
Headlines, you know, are the Tigers, Tigers slaughter the Indians, or something like that, you know, devour the Indians.
Typical sport page, and captioned, and headlines.
He says, I don't know how they read those things.
He said,
He had the same trouble when he went to Germany.
He stayed in Germany for a while, Berlin, and he said he had some of that trouble.
What kind?
I mean, how did he get along with the Germans?
Well, I don't know, but as far as trying to read newspapers and things like that, no.
He went over on the
He inducted Conaway, who was later dean of the veterinary school at Missouri.
But see, he had sent some cattle, a load of cattle up there to Missouri to work on this tick fever problem.
And, oh, that was probably in the 90s, about that time.
I know the same, the dipping vat.
Sure.
First dipping vat that...
It was built in this part of the country.
I think he built it in 96.
He copied it from the King Ranch.
I don't know what the King Ranch was doing with theirs.
They were using it for a different purpose.
But later, of course, they got in forced dipping over the state for these cattle.
But it was all more or less from scratch research work then.
So he and Dr. Conaway went to Europe.
see if they could pick up anything.
But the life history, the life cycle was done right here at the Experiment Station by Cooper Curtis, who was in the Veterinary Science Department under Dr. Francis.
So unless it was to study the organism, but he and Dr. Conway
visit the University of Berlin.
I think they were in Austria, but mainly the University of Berlin.
What do you think Dr. Francis' aim for the vet school was, his goal?
I don't know.
When he, he had a pretty hard time.
The first he started off with a 14 by 16
room in the old main building which was destroyed by fire in 1912.
And that was his office, classroom, and laboratory, 14 by 16.
And it was on the first floor of the old, well that main building was right where the academic building, the one with the dome on it.
And
14 by 16, and the following year they gave him another room.
And for a laboratory, they built him a frame building down pretty close to where the ag building is now, the old ag building.
I think 18 by 30 feet, and that's where he had lab.
And, but...
Shortly after that, they were doing dissecting work in the old natatorium, which they used to have a bathhouse.
The students, instead of having bathing facilities and a dormitory, they used that as a bathhouse down there.
It was between what is now Francis Hall, where the business is.
I don't know.
Between that and the chemistry building.
Facing, well, it would be right on that street, right west of the chemistry building and Francis Hall.
And between that and the Harrington building over there.
Of course, that is a dead end now.
It's a library.
But did he ever talk to you about his aim or his goal?
Well, he mentioned back in 33 when they were tearing down the old veterinary hospital right across the street from the lag building and that later was where the engineering building was built.
He just mentioned that day that
about he says it's on the go now and he says there should be some marked improvements when if and when somebody can produce
I don't recall his exact words, but when they can do something to justify the increase in growth.
But oh my, I don't know whether you could visualize what it's grown into though.
I don't think anybody could do that.
Because in the 60s, when things really took off, that's where the greatest growth has occurred.
But that's beyond, I think, anybody's expectations.
And then this new building is, oh, I don't know.
It started off with, I think, about a $9 million
appropriation for this new clinic building, which is supposed to be operated by May or June 81, I believe.
They started, broke ground on it.
What's going up very quickly now?
Last year, I think in, yeah, broke ground in September 79.
So it's going to take two years.
Why did you say that he was the greatest, about the greatest man that you've ever known?
Well, of his accomplishments and his compassion and his ability, his keenness, able to do research work and teaching and just general viewpoints on life.
And he never called a roll, and I doubt if any student ever cut his classes.
But he had a wonderful way, uncanny way, of evaluating people.
